{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602000/1937090501/0714.xml":{"full_text":"D.C. STORE SALES\nUP332TPER CENT\nABOVE WEEK AGO\nBrisk Capital Rise Leaves\nTotal 7.84 Per Cent Be\nlow 1936 Mark.\nBANK CLEARINGS DROP\nTO $21,125,242 LEVEL\nCompares With $22,400,489 Last\nYear\u2014Building Holds Gain\nWith $682,000 Volume,\nBY HAROLD B. ROGERS.\nWashington retail trade showed a\nbrisk pick-up of 33 21 per cent in\ndepartment stores last week, as com\npared to the previous week, according\nto the Department of Commerce week\nly survey of 37 cities. This, however,\nwas a decrease of 7 84 per cent as\ncompared to last year.\nThe substantial gain was attributed\nto the imminent school openings, im\nproved weather conditions, special\nsales, and the end-of-the-month Gov\nernment pay day.\nClearings were $21,125,242, com\npared with $22,400,489 last year, the\nfirst decrease for 1937. Visitors to\nthe Washington Monument numbered\n30.088, compared with 29,012 last\nweek, and 28,549 a year ago. Building\npermits were $682,000, against $523,\n445 last year. August, 1937, building\npermits stood at $3,157,325. a substan\ntial gain over August last year, of\na too ocn\nRichmond, Va reported that retail\naales in the fifth Federal Reserve dis\ntrict, including this city, showed a\n\u201csubstantial gain over the past week,\nand a slight increase over last year,\nwith increased activity anticipated\nafter Labor day.\"\nIn Baltimore, despite the high tem\nperatures, which were reported to havs\ntended to defer consumer interest in\nFall offerings, retail volume during\nthe past week continued to disclose a\ngeneral upward trend.\nA. I. B. Plans Drive.\nThe annual membership drive of\nWashington Chapter. American Insti\ntute of Banking, will be conducted by\na Membership Committee just ap\npointed, it was announced last night.\nGeorge B. Earnshaw, chairman, has\nhad wide experience with chapter af\nfairs. and was chapter treasurer for\nthe past year. He is associated with\nthe National Metropolitan Bank. Mr.\nEarnshaw will be one of the speakers\nat the educational dinner to be held\nnext Wednesday night at the Willard\nA Hotel.\nThe Membership Committee as an\nnounced by William H. Laughlin,\nchapter president, is as follows:\nEarnshaw, chairman; Bruce Frantz.\nAmerican Security <fc Trust Co.:\nFranklin A. Gibbons, Riggs National\nBank; Frederick C. Loops. Commerce\nSavings; Herbert D. Lawson, Wash\nington Loan Trust Co.; Albert\nGloyd. Union Trust Co.; Dorothy Co\nvert. Security Savings <fe Commercial\nBank: Melvin L. Hamby, National\nMetropolitan Bank; Henry p. Hoff\nman, Second National Bank; Jesse\nCheyney, American Security Trust\nCo Robert M. Poole. Riggs National\nBank; William M. McClure, McLach\nlen Banking Corp.; William Russ, City\nBank.\nAefjpa Life Shows Gains.\nWord has been received by Paul\n\u00abT. Sleeper, general agent of Aetna\nLife Insurance Co that his company\nnow has a total of $3,905,814,023 total\nlife insurance in force, thereby set\nting up \u201ca new all-time record for\nvolume.\" To make this new record,\nAetna Life shows a gain of total in\nsurance amounting to $178,509,468 in\nthe first half of the year. The agency\nhere for Washington and Virginia,\nMr. Sleeper reports, has paid for over\n$6,250,000 of life and group business\nthis year, breaking all past records\nfor a similar period.\nNew home mortgage loans made by\nactive savings, building and loan asso\nciations in the United States during\nJuly aggregated $72,057,000, an in\ncrease of 27 per cent, as compared\nwith $56,855,000 in July, 1936, accord\ning to the Federal Home Loan Bank\nBoard.\nHere in the Winston-Salem, N. C.,\ndistrict, including this city, loans were\n$9,393,000, as compared with $8,759,\n000 for July, 1936.\nSales Parley Called.\n\u2022T. E. Ball, jr\u201e of Chevy Chase,\nmanager of the Washington district of\nthe Monroe Calculating Machine Co.,\nand associates, will spend the week\nof September 7 at the Cloister, Sea\nIsland, Ga\u201e to attend a sales con\nference of the company. He will be\nt accompanied by G. H. Baldwin, W. M.\nMiller and C. A. Wickham. They won\ntheir invitations to the convention by\nqualifying for the High Point Club,\nhonorary sales organizations.\nPersonal Mention.\nEdwin L. Hillyer, vice president of\nUnion Trust Co., returned to his desk\nyesterday from a month's trip abroad.\nGeorge O. Vass, vice president and\neashier of Riggs National Bank, is\nreturning Tuesday from a motor trip\nt through western national parks.\nI. J. Roberts, assistant cashier of\nRiggs National Bank, is leaving for\nvacation on Cape Cod.\nG. Bowie Chipman, resident mana\nger of Laidlaw Co., has returned\nfrom a trip to Europe.\nJesse L. Suter of Laidlaw Co. has\ngone to Virginia Beach on vacation.\nCONSTRUCTION PUSHED\nIN FOOD INDUSTRIES\nSpecial Disputcn to TPe Star. 1\nNEW YORK, September 4.\u2014Awards\nfor construction in the food industries\nduring August, 1937, totaled $3,868,\n000, as compared with $2,256,000 lor\nAugust. 1936, Food Industries reports\nIn its September issue.\nBeverages led in awards for the\nmonth with $1,475,000; grain products\nsecond with $1,000,000. In pending\nprojects the total for the month was\n$8,288,000. Beverages also led with\n$5,210,000; grain mill products second\nwith $1,260,000.\nTotal awards for construction in\n1937 thus lar, $27,520,000.\nTOBACCO INDEX HIGHER.\nNEW YORK, September 4 The\naverage price of United States type\ns \u201cIS,\u201d grade B4F,\" flue-cured tobacco\nfor the week ended September 4 was\n19.2 eents a pound, compared with 19\ncents the previous week and 18.1 cents\na year ago, H. A. Stich, tobacco econ\nomist, reported.\nV l\nFALL REVIVAL FORECAST\nBY STANDARD STATISTICS\nBig Agency Sees No Reason to Change\nPredictions for Full Seasonal\nUpturn in Coming Months.\nSpecial Dispatch to Tha Star.\nNEW YORK. September 4.\u2014In it*\nweekly summary of the general busi\nness situation the Standard Statistics\nCo. of New York, currently comments\nas follows:\n\u201cThere is a growing belief in some\nquarters that Instead of enjoying a\nfull seasonal recovery this Pall, busi\nness activity will be well below earlier\nexpectations. It has been pointed out\nthat to date there are no signs of any\nimprovement; that production and\norders in many lines are continuing to\ndecline; that the favorable effect of\nthe larger crops will be more than off\nset by the decline in prices, and that\nbusiness generally during the next four\nmonths may. therefore, compare un\nfavorably with the satisfactory levels\nprevailing a year earlier.\n\u201cWe see no reason, however, to\nchange our previous forecast* that a\nfull seasonal upturn in industrial ac\ntivity will be witnessed this Pall. It la\nnot at all surprising that certain lines\nhave failed to record Improvement in\nrecent weeks, as business generally sle\ndom begins its Pall upturn until it\nweek or two after Labor day. In fact,\nbecause of the smaller number of\nworking days in September, it is un\nlikely that aggregate volume this\nmonth will be much, if any, better\nthan in August.\n\"It should be noted that, although\nindustrial production has been de\nclining irregularly since March, the\nrecession has been mild and activity is\nstill holding well above year-earlier\nlevels. Considering the season of the\nyear, many industries, including steel,\nsutomobiles and farm machinery, are\nmaintaining operations at a highly\nsatisfactory rate.\u201d\nCOTTON FOLLOWS\nUNEVEN COURSE\nAT WEEK\u2019S CLOSE\nPrices 6 Higher to 9 Lower.\nFederal Crop Estimate\nDue Wednesday.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. September 4.\u2014-Cotton\nwas irregular today as traders evened\nup accounts for over the holiday week\nend and prior to the Government crop\nindication on Wednesday. December,\nwhich had recovered from 9 12 to 9 23,\neased to close at 9 10, with final prices\n6 points net higher to 9 lower.\nThe market opened unchanged to 4\npoints lower. Increased Southern sell\ning and liquidation was soon absorbed\nby trade price-fixing and foreign\nbuying.\nAs contracts became scarce during\nthe middle of the morning, the market\nrallied to net gains of 7 to 11 points\non further trade buying and some local\ncovering.\nThe bulges attracted increased offer\nings. however, especially from the\nSouth and all months closed at the\nlows for the day except October, which\nended practically at the best on trade\ncovering.\nA substantial increase in the crop in\nall sections of Texas was indicated by\na Dallas newspaper in its weekly sum\nmary of conditions for that State.\nAmount of cotton on shipboard\nawaiting clearance at the end of the\nweek was estimated at 44.000 bales,\nagainst 32.000 last week and 19.000\nlast year.\nThe range follows:\nHl*h Low Lust\nOctober p-js i j.'l ft \"\u2022'-\u2022\u2019S\nDecember p,-;:i p in pm-Ii\nJanuary _ p-'p p);i\nMarch -P 40 P.C.'i p-\\V\u2019\u00ab\nM\u00bby PAP P.94 P.94\n9.52 9.42 9 49-44\nSpot steady; middling 9.42.\nuriean* Prices.\nNEW ORLEANS September 4\nCotton futures closed barely steadv at net\ndeclines of 2 to ft points.\n_ Open. H\u2018*h- Vow. Close.\nOctober 9.1 1 9.74 9.11 9.14-17\nDecember 9.22 9.30 9.20 9 M-\"3\nJanuary 9.27 9.30 9.2H 9\nMarch 9.33 9 41 9 31 9 31\nMav 9.44 9.ft2 9.4! 9.4 1-42\nJuly P.5H 9.SH 9.49 9 49\nCotton seed oil closed steady: bleacliable\nprime Summer yellow. 7.80 nominal\n5r me crude, fi 37\u2018i-ti.fto. September.'\nI Mb: October, 7.17b: December. 7.17b\nJanuary 7.19b. March, 7.24b.\nb\u2014Bid. a\u2014Asked.\nGOOD TRADE EXPECTED\nFOR REMAINDER OF 1937\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. September 4.\u2014\"Busi\nness is good; this Fall it will be better,\nbut it's not likely to be brilliant,\u201d is\nBusiness Week's analysis of the out\nlook for the remaining months of\n1937.\n\"Moderate improvement is looked\nfor, sustained by increased farm pur\nchasing power, higher wages, fat divi\ndends aided and abetted by the undis\ntributed earnings tax, and continued\ngain in the number of people em\nployed. Compared svith 1936, all\nthese factors should be better.\n\"Industrial activity, which has been\nmafking time since mid-January,\nshould step out of its groove to sur\npass the year-end spurt of 1936. But\nvisions of 1929 are a bit on the balmy\nside.\u201d\nRAIL ORDERS LARGE.\nClass 1 railroads installed 41.630\nnew freight cars, 198 new steam loco\nmotives and 25 new electrical and\nDiesel locomotives In the first seven\nmonths of 1937.\nCHANGES SLIGHT\nON WHEAT MARKET\nAS VOLUME LAGS\nArgentine Rains and Decline\nat Buenos Aires Weak\nening Factors.\nBY FRANKLIN MULLIN',\nAssociated Press Market Writer.\nCHICAGO. September 4.\u2014Wheat\nprices bobbed above and below the\nprevious closing level today, winding\nup practically unchanged.\nThe market's upward tendency was\nchecked by feebleness of speculative\ndemand prior to the double holiday.\nFurthermore, cabled reports of more\nrainfall in Argentina, along with the\nlower close at Buenos Aires were\nweakening influences.\nThe quiet trade was canfined largely\nto traders' activity in evening up ac\ncounts, many not wishing to hold a\nmarket position through Monday,\nI when foreign exchanges will be in\noperation, but domestic markets will\nbe closed.\nAt the final bcl: wheat was\nhigher to 1 g lower compared with yes\nterday's finish, September, 1.05%-%;\nDecember. 1.07%-%; May, 109%-%;\ncorn was %-l% up; September, 97%\nDecember, 63%-%; May, 64%-%;\noats up to down: September. 30;\nrye. lower: September, 80%;\nprovisions, 3 to 15 higher.\nLiverpool Prices Up.\nA advance at Liverpool, which\nwas much better than due. brought\nan upward swing of about cent in\nChicago wheat at the opening, but at\n$1.06 for September and $1.08 for De\ncember the buying dried up and the\nmarket sagged about 1% cents. Cables\nreporting good soaking rains still are\nneeded in Argentina to make a crop\nof 200.000.000 bushels or better and\na report, from Australia emphasizing\nthe lower condition of new wheat in\nVictoria and New South Sales which\ncontain nearly half of the common\nwealth s acreage, were associated with\nthe upturn.\novernight export sales of Canadian\nwheat were estimated at 400,000 bush\nels and a little domestic hard Winter\nbusiness also was reported along with\nnews from Washington of the adoption\nof special certificates to facilitate do\nmestic wheat exports via the lakes\nand Canadian seaports.\nCorn Values Higher.\nThere was talk that importers were\nunderstood to be growing apprehensive\nnot so much over ability to obtain\nwheat, but over growing tightness of\nthe ocean freight market, together with\npossibility of further increases in rates.\nTraders said this situation might result\nin a larger demand for wheat to take\nadvantage of current rates.\nSeptember corn moved ovef a 2-cent\nrange and closed sharply higher on\nshort covering. There was a slight\nincrease in the open interest Friday.\nInstead of the expected decrease. New\n(See WHEAT, PageD^8)\nCLEARING HOUSE ISSUES\nREPORT AT NEW YORK\nBr the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. September 4.\u2014The\nweekly statement of the New York\nClearing House shows:\nTotal surplus and undivided profits\nunchanged at $894,463,200. Total net\ndemand deposits (average) increased\n$29,189,000. Time deposits (average)\ndecreased $419,000. Clearings week\nending today, $3,395,988,463. Clearings\nweek ending August 28, $2,908,686,804.\nHow Is Business?\nShowing Current Business Activity Compared With the Same Week a Tear Afo. 1\nGENERAL BUSINESS ACTIVITY for the country Indicated by Bank Debits outside\nN. Y. City. 8haded areas show week of activity above tbs corresponding week af tba\nprevious year. Black araaa Indicate declines from same weeks twelve months earlier.\nACTIVITY BY FEDERAL RESERVE DISTRICTS\nCheek Transactions compared with tbs same weak s year ago_\nBoston New York Philadelphia Cleveland I DsImaZ J Atlanta\n+4.7% -1E.1* +9.2% +19.4% I _ +4-9%_|\nChicago it. Leals I Minneapolis I Kansas City Dallas IS. Prsaslees\nI +13-4% I +9.lg\"l +17J* +23.7% I +34.1%l\nLEADING BAROMETERS\nShowing Trend of Important Factors\nPresent Trend From Year Age\nBusiness In Dollars (Checks Cashed) Downward 12.8\nEmployment (Dept, of Labor). Upward 4. IIS\nWages (Dept, of Labor). Downward 26.1\nCost of Living (Ind. Conf. Board)... Steady X 4.3\nWholesale Prices (Fisher's Index).. Downward 9.4\nAgricultural Prices (Bureau of Labor) Downward x 2.9\nMovement of Goods (Car Loadings). Upward 4> 6.2\nRetail Trade (Fed. Res. Board). Upward 3.2\nBuilding Contracts (F. W. Dodge).. Downward 4- 33.9\nFailures (Dun\u2019s). V Upward +17.7\nBond Prices (Dow-Jones). Downward 3.8\nStock Prices (Composite Dow*Jones) Downward l.g\nStock Mkt. Vol. (Shares Traded)... Downward 88.9\nAHrighi1 resort**/, Cmbrtdgi Amoc&m, Boston\n1 l\nSTOCKS ARE DULL\nWITH FEW STEELS\nAND RAILS HIGHER\nSome Specialties Also Gain.\nMany Other Issues Go\nDown Moderately.\nU. S. GOVERNMENT BONDS\nCONTINUE TO RETREAT\nRailroad Obligations Also Slump.\nLack of Support Rather Than\nSize of Offerings Blamed.\nBY FREDERICK GARDNER.\nAssociated Press Financial Writer.\nNEW YORK, September 4.\u2014Finan\ncial markets merely dozed today and\nprice changes In virtually all depart\nments were meaningless.\nStocks limped ahead, with a few\nsteels, rails and specialties getting up\na [joint or so. Many issues were at a\nstandstill and moderate losses were\nplentiful at the close.\nTransfers of 229.980 shares were the\nsmallest for any day since June 19.\nThe turnover of about *2.000,000 in\nbonds established a low mark for the\npast seven years or longer. Prices In\nthe loans division were uneven.\nThe apathy of preholiday stock deal\nings was exemplified by the fact only\n486 separate Issues changed hands,\ncompared with 728 yesterday. The\nAssociated Press average of 60 stocks\nmanaged to hold a gain of 0.1 of a\npoint, at 63.7.\nThe ticker tape was frequently mo\ntionless. Board rooms were virtually\ndeserted as traders seemingly found\nmore profit in starting their lengthy\nrecess early than in attempting to out\nguess share trends.\nProminent on the up side were shares\nof United States Steel at 104%, Beth\nlehem, 90%; General Motors, 53%;\nGeneral Electric, 51%; Canada Dry,\n23%: New York Central, 34%; Great\nNorthern, 46%; Santa Fe, 68%: Ana\nconda. 53%; Pacific Gas, 30%: Ameri\ncan Water Works, 17%: Paramount,\n21%; Standard Oil of New Jersey,\n63\\; Texas Corp., 56%: American\nBrake Shoe, 55, and Commercial In\nvestment Trust. 58%.\nJohns-Manville was an isolated weak\nspot, dropping 4 at 117%. Lesser de\nclines were registered for J. I. Case,\nat 152; Marshall Field. 23%: National\nGypsum, 9%; Goodyear, 35%: Servel,\n25: Sears-Roebuek, 86%; Allied Stores,\n16%; Chrysler, 106%, and Philip Mor\nris. 93%.\nFederal Ronds Down- j\nUnited States Government bonds\nand railroad obligations drooped in a j\nshrunken bond market. With turn- i\nover at a post-depression low and the\ntrading fraternity thinned by ab-1\nsentees, price shifts were confined to\nnarrow bounds.\nLosses in Ftderals ranged as high\nas 8-32 of a point, while gains, which j\nwere few, were held to around 4-32 of j\na point. Transactions in this section\nwere in the neighborhood of $200,000\nface amount.\nRailroad liens stumbled down. Lack\nof support and thinness of the mar\nket rather than weight of offerings\nhastened their fall. The Associated\nPress averages for 20 rail issues\nshowed a drop of 0.1 of a point to 89 3,\nthe lowest point since January. 1936\nIndustrial issues managed to hold\na fairly unbroken front, while certain\nsections of the utility division lifted a\nlittle. Interest In all groups was at\na low ebb. The averages for 10 in\ndustrial hens was unchanged at 102 8,\nwhile 10 utilities advanced 0.3 of a\npoint to 97.4.\nmufcuiciiv 111 iuiri\u00a7u uunai uuuua\nwas restricted to fractions. Japanese\nloans weds uneven and little definite i\ntrend in either direction was discern\nible throughout most of the list.\nTurnover for all bonds totaled $2,\n000.500 face value, the lowest In more\nthan seven years, compared with $2,\n473,400 on last Saturday.\nCurb Changes Small.\nA few oils and utilities drifted a\nlittle higher in one of the lightest\nsessions the curb market has experi\nenced in two and a half years. Price\nshifts in both directions were held to\nnarrow fractions.\nElectric Bond Share crept up a\nminor fraction to 16 and Creole Pe\ntroleum advanced to 33Tg. Arkan\nsas Natural Gas \u2018'A.\u201d Niagara Hud\nson Power, St. Regis Paper and Hecla\nMining lifted minor fractions.\nSlipping minor fractions were Hum\nble Oil at 80?i, American Cyanamid\n\"B\u201d at 337i and International Pe-!\ntroleum at 34,/2. United Gas, Wright\nHargreaves, Sunray Oil and Fisk Rub\nber were unchanged.\nVolume totaled 55,000 shares, the\nlowest since March 9, 1935. compared\nwith 65,000 shares last Saturday.\nTHRIFT ENCOURAGEMENT\nURGED BY U. S. OFFICIAL\nPopular misinterpretations of aocial\nsecurity and similar protective legis\nlation make necessary the encourage\nment of thrift, particularly through\nmodernised savings and loan asso\nciations, Dr. Henry E. Hoagland, a\nmember of the Federal Home Loan\nBank Board, urged in a statement to\nsavings and loan executives yester\nday.\n\"The continued growth of our social\nand economic institutions requires\nthat we maintain thrift as one of our\noutstanding, virtues and use every\nreasonable means to protect the fruits\nof thrifty habits,\u201d he stated.\n\"At best, workmen\u2019s compensation\nlaws, sickness and unemployment in\nsurance and old-age pensions are in\ntended to provide only minimum sub\nsistence and protection to the bene\nficiaries of such programs.\u201d\nMUNICIPAL FINANCING\nDROPS BELOW YEAR AGO\nSpecial Difpatcrt to The Star.\nNEW YORK. September 4.\u2014State\nand municipal financing for the\nmonth of August aggregated $53,771,*\n264, as compared with $87,447,141 In\nAugust, 1936, according to the Dally\nBond Buyer of New York.\nThe total for the first eight months\nof 1937 is $728,910,782, as compared\nwith $746,129,668 for the same period\nlast year.\nR. F. C. financing during August,\n1937, totaled $1,021,000, as compa/ed\nwith $14,356,000 during August last\nyear. P. W. A. financing reported tor\nAugust of this year totaled $41,500, as\ncompared with $111,006 in August,\nISM.\nMISSED AGAIN.\nXRY XBOWfrtCt HIM -j\nLittle higher\n\u00abKEXT T1MS.WP cot\nQUITS JWAOrf'\n.\u2022HM/\nV*\n\nTHEYvt BEEN X\nI advertising they\nVJERC GOING Tr DO 1\nI 'THAT TTRICK EVERY)\nYEAR. FOR FIVE\nV YEARS ^>-w.\nJ 1 t(\nRADIO FIRMS SEE\nPrepare to Meet New High\nLevel in Volumes Dur\ning Autumn.\n\nSpecial Dupater to The Star.\nNEW YORK. September 4\u2014The\nradio industry is preparing to meet\na new high level in sales volume dur\ning the Fall selling season, according\nto Poor's Stock Reports. Estimates as\nto the demand for new sets this year\nrun between 9.000.000 and 10.000.000 j\nunits. Furthermore, a favorable trend\nis being experienced in sales volume\nof radio tubes.\n\"The prospect of record unit de\nmand is further enhanced by the gen\neral trend toward mark-ups, ranging\nfrom about $3 to more than $15 per\nlet,\" the report states. \"This should\npermit the industry to offset the ris\ning material and labor costs, which\nhave developed during the current\nyear. The trade expects a considerable\npart of the record demand will come\nfrom the farm population areas. Sta\ntistics show that about 5.000.000 farm\nhouses must depend on battery oper\nated sets. Even granting completion\nif the Government's rural electrifica\ntion program, it is estimated that there\nwill still be 4.000.000 farms without\nelectric lines in 1945.\n\"Zenith Radio, the second largest\nset manufacturer, stands to show\nfurther earnings gains. The company\nhas been a leader in the production\nif farm sets since its introduction of a\nnew' line of battery operated sets two\nyears ago. Profits for the fiscal year\nsnded April, 1937, established a new\npeak, despite the necessity of restrict\ned output in the final quarter, occa\nsioned by moving to a new plant. It is\nprobable that earnings for the current\nfiscal year will approximate $8 per\nshare.\n\"Radio Corp. Is experiencing good\nearnings improvement, with net profit\namounting to $4,647,000 in the first\nhalf of 1937, as compared with $1,\n764,000 for the like 1936 interval. With\nthe seasonably profitable months\nihead there is likelihood of a nominal\ndividend on the common stock before\nfhe year end. This would be the first\npayment on the equity issue since\ncompany's organization.\u201d\nFOREIGN COPPER\nSLUMPS FURTHER\nFails to Influence Domestic\nQuotation of 14 Cents, but\nBuyers Hold Off.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, September 4\u2014Gen\nerally quiet conditions prevailed in\nthe non-ferrous metals during the\npast week.\nFurther moderate declines in the\nForeign copper price, while not in\nFluencing the 14-cent domestic elec\ntrolytic quotations, caused consumers\nto hold off. Producers, who adhered\nto their asking prices, were well sup\nplied with unfilled backlogs of orders.\nA slight partial recovery in the Euro\npean price occurred late in the week.\nAntimony advanced about 2% cents\nin two weeks for Chinese grades. Sup\nplies are reported to be seriously cur\ntailed as a result of the Far Eastern\nlostiUtiea and world demand has cor\nrespondingly become more Insistent,\nrhe demand, however, was aaid to be\nmostly for export with domestic buy\ning held down to moderate propor\ntions because of sharply higher prices.\nTin moved Irregularly In response\nto changes at London, but displayed\nlittle net alteration ~ln prices for the\nweek.\nLead was quiet and unchanged, al\nthough unevenly distributed business\nFor September shipment was reported\nby some smelters. Zinc trading was\npf small proportions largely because\nat the tight September supply situa\ntion.\nCOTTON AVERAGE DOWN.\nNEW ORLEANS, September 4 UP).\u2014\nrhe average price of middling cotton\ntoday at 10 Southern spot markets\nwas 9.14 cents a pound: average for\nthe past 90 market days, 10.09 cents\na pound.\nA\nConference Held\nOn U. S. Treasury\nJ\nFinancing Plans\nBy the Associated Press.\nMembers of the Federal Reserve\nBoard's Open Market Committee met\nwith Secretary Morgenthau yesterday\nfor a discussion of the Treasury's Sep\ntember financing.\nThe committee, which governs Re\nserve Board policy In buying and sell\ning Government securities, customarily\nis consulted on Treasury borrowing.\nOn September 15. the Treasury will\noffer $817,000,000 of new securities in\nexchange for a like amount of matur\ning 3't per cent notes. Morgenthau\nwill announce the type of new securi\nties Tuesday.\nSUGAR SHIPMENTS\nON QUOTAS SHOWN\n4,032.157 Toni Charged Against\nAllowable of 4.966.579 in\nFirst Fight Months.\nBy the Associated Press.\nThe Agricultural Adjustment Ad\nministration announced yesterday\nthat 4,032.157 tons of sugar had been\ncharged against the 1937 quotas of\n4.966.579 tons for all offshore areas,\nincluding free-duty countries, during\nthe first eight months of this year.\nAmounts charged against these sup\nply sources and the 1937 quotas fol\nlow;\nCuba, 1.785,210 tons for January,\nagainst quota of 2.014.538 tons; Phil\nippines. 747,139, against 1.085.304;\nPuerto Rico, 826.311, against 840.954;\nHawaii, 652,736. against 988.551; Vir-{\ngin Islands. 5,475, against 9,396, and\nforeign countries other than Cuba,\n15,286, against 27.836.\nRefined sugar shipments, included\nwithin the general quotas, showed\nCuba had nearly exhausted its 1937\ntotal of 371,058 tons. The balance\nat the start of this month was 3,942\ntons.\nPuerto Rico has exhausted its 126,\n033-ton quota for refined. The Phil\nippines had a balance of 19.321 tons\nof its total of 60,893, and Hawaii a\nbalance of 9,703 tons of its 1937 quota\nof 19,913.\nCHAIN DRUG VOLUMES\nCLIMB 4.3 PER CENT\nAverage dally gales of chain drug\nstores in July, 1937, were 4.3 per cent\nhigher than in July, 1936, according\nto preliminary estimates of the Bu\nreau of Foreign and Domestic Com\nmerce. July, 1937, sales were up 0.9\nper cent from June, 1937, no adjust\nment being made for seasonal vari\nation.\nThe greatest gain was shown by\ntobacco sales, which were 7.8 per cent\nhigher, followed by \"all other\u201d sales\nwith a 2.6 per cent increase from last\nJuly, while fountain sales Increased\n0.3 per cent.\nTobacco sales increased in relative\nimportance over July of last year,\nwhile the other two classifications\nshowed decreases in this ratio. To\nbacco sales and fountain sales com\nbined accounted for 46.0 per cent of\ntotal sales this July, as against 45.5\nper cent in July, 1936.\n\nCARRIERS REPLACE TIES.\nApproximately 47,500,000 cross ties\nwere replaced in 1936 by the railroads,\nor enough to build 16,000 miles of\ntrack.\nI\n8-YEAR PEAK SET\nBY RUBBER TRADE\nSales of Industrial Goods\nSoar 25 to 45 Per Cent\nAbove Year Ago.\n8p\u00abi\u00bbl Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, September 4\u2014Half\nyear totals for both production and\ndistribution in most divisions of the\nrubber goods industry moved up to\nan eight-year high, according to a\nsurvey by Dun <fe Bradstreet, Inc.\nAlthough production of automobile\ntires started downward in April, and\nby June was under last year's rate,\nat the majority of other plants sched\nules were unchanged. The W'idest gain\nfor the first six months was recorded\nfor industrial rubber goods, sales of\nwhich rose 25 to 45 per cent from the\n1936 comparative, with a new record\nestablished for the distribution of some\nfactory equipment lines, office supplies\nand novelties.\n\"For the first time since 1928 an\nincrease in replacement tire sales over\nthe preceding year's is indicated.\nTrade estimates have set the 1937 total\nat 31.200.000 tires, as compared with\n29,700,000 in 1936, an increase of 5.1\nper cent. As the estimate for original\nequipment, however, has been stepped\ndown to 25,000,000 tires, the total\n1937 automobile tire production will\nbe lowered to 56,200,000 units, a de\ncline of 3t3 per cent from the 1936\nproduction of 58.116,000, as compiled\nby the Rubber Manufacturers\u2019 Asso\nciation, Inc., and the first drop since\n1932.\n\"Even should the current tense labor\nsituation in the tire division reach a\ncrisis, when planned large-scale lay\noffs start, the closing of all plants by\na strike for the remainder of 1937\nwould cause no inconvenience to\neither automobile producer* or users.\nAt mid-August inventories were the\nlargest on record, plants holding\naround 12,500.000 units, dealers abouj.\n7,000.000 and automobile manufac\nturers 3.000.000.\n\u201cReduction of operations in many\ndivisions of the industry, which started\nin June, did not prevent production\nfor the first six months from surpass\ning that of 1936. Renewed activity of\nIdle equipment and long-needed re\npairs and replacements by heavy users\nbolstered output of industrial rubber\nproducts from 20 to 50 per cent above\nlast year's. In some lines of belting,\npacking, washers and Insulating ma\nterials the comparative gain exceeded\nthe top range. On rubber novelties,\noffice specialties, footwear and coats\nmany factories were booked months\nahead.\u201d\nDRIED EGG SHIPMENTS\nBLOCKED BY CONFLICT\nBr the Associated Press.\nHostilities in China have blocked\ndried egg shipments to the United\nStates, the Bureau of Agricultural\neconomics reported.\nShanghai is the most important egg\ndrying center in China, the bureau\nsaid, and almost the entire stocks\n\u201care in the fighting zone and in\ndanger of destruction by Are and\nshelling.\u201d\nRemoval from storage was termed\nimpossible by the bureau\u2019s observer,\nwho reported plants are not operating.\nDried eggs are used principally in\nbaking bread and cakes.\n\nWeekly Financial High Lights\nBr the Associated Press. This week. Prev week. Year ago.\nBrokers\u2019 loans.... *1.171.000 *1,140,000 9084,000\nHoldings U. S. securities. 2,526,190 2,526,190 2.430,227\nGold reserve.\u2014 8,831,389 8,831)948 8,334,034\nRediscounts... 23.726 18,703 8,602\nBank Clearings_ 5,524,337 4,759,835 5,842,270\nElectric output, kilowatt hours,\nweek ended August 28. 2,294,713 2,304,032 2,125,502\n(Final three ciphers omitted in above.)\nOar loadings, week ended August 28.. 787,373 781,247 754,097\nCrude oil production, barrels_ 3,731,450 3,729,350 3,032,050\nStock sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange.. 3,903,030 3,750,550 6,580,590\nBond sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange... *28,003,300 *35,678,475 *62,848,000\nNew financing__ 18,431,100 38,477,000 79,335,000\nFederal Reserve ratio__ 79.5% 79.7% 79.4%\nSteel output rate_ 84.1% 83.8% 71.5%\nCall money rate........ 1% 1% 1%\nTime money rate.........\u2014....\u2014 iy\u00ab-lH% iy\u00ab%\nCommercial paper. 1% 1%\na A\nTRADE IRREGULAR\nDESPITE ADVANCES\nIN SOME QUARTERS\nRetail Volumes Increase,\nbut Uniform Optimism\nAppears Lacking.\nLOADINGS SCORE GAINS\nWITH STEEL ACTIVITY\nContrast With Seasonal Decline*\nin Auto and Power Totals.\nIndex Off Slightly.\nBY THOMAS E. FLANAGAN,\nAsioelittd Press Financial Writ,r.\nSome divisions of the Nation's trade\nand industry faltered last week, while\nothers continued to drive forward with\ngood momentum.\nAlong the industrial front gains\nscored by steel operations and car\nloadings contrasted with seasonal de\nclines in automobile and electric power\noutput.\nThe Associated Press index of in\ndustrial activity declined to 104 from\n104 4 the week previous and compared\nwith 95.2 in the like week last year.\nWhile reports to the Department of\nCommerce from 37 key cities indi\ncated unmistakable progress in retail\ntrade in widespread areas, \"the re\nviews were not of sufficiently uniform,\noptimism to warrant the uncondi\ntional conclusion that the pending\nFall season is to usher in a period of\nmore than ordinary seasonal activity.\"\nMixed conditions prevailed in whole,\nsale markets, the survey said\nIn the steel industry operations were\nstepped up to 84 1 per cent of capacity\nfrom 83 8 the week before and 71.5 m\nthe corresponding week of 1936.\nSome Doubt Evident.\na snaaow oi aoubt crossed the\nminds of steel men on the outlook\nThey said in the absence of clear\nindications there was tendency spread\ning in steel circles to question whether\nFall business will come up to esti\nmates posted earlier in the Summer.\nTrade observers said potential de\nmand for light steel products was the\nmost promising aspect of the current\nsituation. With production of new\ncar models in the offing, they said,\nthere would likely be a quickened\ndemand for sheet and strip products.\nAt the same time hopes were held\nfor wider sales of miscellaneous light\nsteels.\nOn the other hand, they argued\nbuying of heavy steels might be con\nsiderably less aggressive. Building\nconstruction has been disappointing,\nit was said, and the number of new\nprojects in sight brings little prospect\nof important business from this quar\nter.\nThe Association of American Rail\nroads reported loadings of 787.373 cars\nin the week ended August 28. an in\ncrease of 0.8 of 1 per cent over tha\npreceding week and a gain of 4.4 per\ncent over the like 1936 week.\nTraffic analysts said railroads would\nprobably benefit from a rise in load\nings to a Fall peak estimated at around\n960.000 cars a week, a level which\nwould compare with 826.155, the high\nreached last Fall in the week ended\nOctober 17.\nAuto Production Sags.\nAutomobile output declined to 64,200\ncars from 83.310 the week previous\nand compared with 31.601 in the cor\nresponding week a year ago, Ward's\nreported.\nAside from the production drop,\nwhich was occasioned by preparations\nfor the manufacture of new models,\nthe interest of the trade focused on the\nforecast of Alfred P. Sloan, jr., chair\nman of the board of General Motors\nCorp, that higher operating costs\nwould bring an upturn in prices on\n1938 models.\nWhile the price mark-up Is likely\nto slow down distribution, this would\nprobably be only temporary, he added.\nAnalysts curious about the effect of\nthe Far Eastern conflict on American\nbusiness noted Sloan's statement the\ncompany has done a good volume with\nJapan and has not yet been affected\nby the strife. Overseas trade other\nwise, he said, was \"very good\nProduction of electricity in the week\nended August 28 was a little lower at\n2.294.713.000 kilowatt hours, the Edison\nElectric Institute reported. The total\nwas 8 per cent ahead of the like week\nof 1936. compared with a gain of 10\nper cent scored in the week ended\nAugust ii.\nPower Rate Stable.\nNoting that for the sixtieth con\nsecutive week the output was above\nthe 2.000.000.000 kilowatt hour mark,\npower experts attributed steadiness of\nproduction to both widened domestic\ndemand and the well-sustained pace of\nIndustry.\nIt was stressed, nevertheless, that the\ngain over 1936 In the central Indus\ntrial region had narrowed considerably\nowing in some measure to alower\nmotor output. The gain In this dis\ntrict In the week ended August 18 was\n9.5 per cent, compared with 13.3 In\nthe week ended August 21.\nReflecting traders\u2019 fears over the Far\nEastern struggle, heightened tension\nIn the Mediterranean and uncertainties\nover the Fall business outlook, share\nprices on the New York Stock Ex\nchange fell back, but regain balance\nat the close of the week.\nThe bond market saw' United Stales\nGovernment and railroad Issues de\ncline on small trading. Drops in\nTreasury loans, bond men said, bore\nwitness to preparations for new Gov\nernment financing. Lower carrier\nprices were eiyjlained partly in terms\nof higher railway operating costs.\nCommodities declined, the average\nof leading staples dipping for the\nthird consecutive week to a new 1937\n(See TRADE, Page D-8.)\nWAD ASKS APPROVAL\nOF $30,000,000 BONDS\nBy the Associated Press.\nThe Duluth, Missabe St Iron Range\nRailway Co. asked Interstate Com\nmerce Commission authority yesterday\n10 issue *30,000,000 of 3 Vs per een*\nIrst mortgage bonds.\nThe transaction Is In connection\nwith plans to merge four subsidiary\n\u25a0allroads of the United States Steel\n2orp.\nOf the total. *19.500,000 would ba\nssued to the Minnesota Iron Co. in\nexchange for all its capital stock of\nthe Duluth St Iron Range Railroad\n3o.t and *500,000 to the Agate Land\n-o. in exchange for its outstanding\nitock of the Interstate Transfer Rail\nway Co.\nThe remainder of the issue would\nse sold for cash\n1","height":"31180","width":"22272"}}
